<p><blockquote><h5>Definition.</h5>
Given two groups $(G, *)$ and $(G', *')$, the <b>product group</b>
$G\times G'$ is the set $\{(g, g'), g \in G, g\in G'\}$
equipped with the group operation defined by $(a, a')\cdot(b, b') = (a*b, a'*'b')$.
The identity element of $G\times G'$ is $(e_G, e_{G'})$,
and $(g, g')^{-1} = (g^{-1}, g'^{-1})$ for all $(g, g') \in G\times G'$.
<p></blockquote><hr>
<p><blockquote><h5>Theorem.</h5>
Let $G$ be a group.  If $H$, $K$ are subgroup of $G$ such that $HK = G$, $H \cap K = \{e\}$,
and every element of $H$ commutes with every element of $K$, then:
\[
G \cong H \times K.
\]
<p></blockquote><hr>
Define a map $\phi : H \times K \ra G$ as follows:
\[
\phi(h, k) = hk,\quad \text{ for all } (h, k) \in H \times K.
\]
Since elements in $H$ commute with those of $K$,
we have
\[
\phi((h, k)(h', k')) = \phi(hh', kk') = hh'kk' = hkh'k' = \phi(h, k)\phi(h', k'),
\]
for all $(h, k), (h', k') \in H \times K$.  Hence, $\phi$ is a homomorphism.
Moreover, since by assumption $HK = G$, the map $\phi$ is surjective.

An element $(h, k) \in H\times K$ lies in $\ker \phi$ if and only if $hk = e$,
which holds if and only if $h = k^{-1}$, which belongs to $K$.  Since $H \cap K = \{e\}$, an element $h \in H$
lies in $K$ if and only if $h = e$.  Consequently, $(h , k) \in \ker \phi$ if and only if $h = k = e$.
So, $\phi$ is a one-to-one and onto homomorphism.  Hence, it is an isomorphism.

<p><blockquote><h5>Claim.</h5>
Let $G$ be a finite abelian group.  For any prime $p$ which divides $\abs{G}$,
there is an element $g \in G$ with order $p$.
<p></blockquote><hr>
We prove the claim via induction on $\abs{G}$, with base case $\abs{G} = p$.

If $\abs{G} = p$, then we have already seen that every non-identity element of $G$ has order $p$.

Now suppose $\abs{G} > p$, and the claim holds for all finite abelian groups $G'$ such that $p | \abs{G'}$
and $\abs{G'} < \abs{G}$.

Let $g$ be a non-identity element of $G$.  Let $H$ be the subgroup
$\langle g \rangle \subseteq G$.  If $p | \abs{H}$, say $\abs{H} = pl$ for some $l \in \mathbb{N}$,
then it is clear that $a^l$ has order $p$.
If $p \nmid \abs{H}$, consider the quotient group $G/H$, which is finite abelian.
By Lagrange's theorem, $\abs{G/H} = [G:H] = \abs{G}/\abs{H}$.  Since $p \nmid \abs{H}$ and $p | \abs{G}$,
we must have $p | \abs{G/H}$.  This means that $G/H$ is a finite abelian group with order divisible by $p$.
Since, $\abs{G/H} < \abs{G}$, by the inductive hypothesis there exists an element $gH \in G/H$
which has order $p$.  In other words, $g^p \in H$.  On the other hand, $g$ is an element of the finite group $G$,
so it has some finite order $m$ such that $g^m = e$.  Hence, $(gH)^m = eH = H$ in $G/H$, which implies that $p | m$.
We have $(g^{m/p})^p = e$, which implies that $\ord g^{m/p} | p$.  Since $p$ is prime and $g^{m/p} \neq e$,
we conclude that $g^{m/p}$ has order $p$.


